line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Even though the art market looks to auctions to=
 set the headline
prices that drive sales across the secondary market (and often have strong =
effects on primary market pricing, too), people like Hoffman and former auc=
tioneer <strong>Jussi Pylkk=C3=A4nen</strong> are pointing to the robust pr=
ivate market and suggesting it might remain the preferred arena for sellers=
=2E Let=E2=80=99s not sleep on this predic=
tion, because it could have a profo=
und effect on the tenor and tone of the art market. The possibility that th=
e top of the market continues to be hidden in private sales is
an enormous deal, and probably a subject for another column, soon.=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;">Meanwhile, the search for a new narrative=E2=80=94a colle=
cting thesis that redefines the pecking order in terms of art history, popu=
larity, and value=E2=80=94may be the overriding theme of the current market=
=2E A narrative is what lures the ma=
rginal buyers=E2=80=94the ones who are fo=
llowing other collectors without, possibly, fully understanding their
rationale. The art world tends to call these spendy buyers =E2=80=9Cspecula=
tors,=E2=80=9D but they=E2=80=99re really the opposite, and their disappear=
ance is one reason the market feels like it has lost energy.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">When y=
ou see commentators like <strong>Amy Cappellazzo </strong>note in <em>The A=
rt Newspaper </em>that we live in a bland, algorithmically attenuated infor=
mation environment, part of what she=E2=80=99s saying is that we need a new
thesis=E2=80=94actually, many new theses. =E2=80=9CThinking and betting bra=
vely on something less than obvious,=E2=80=9D Cappellazzo <a href=3D"https:=
//email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVUTFHUE9kN=
